@Node "Starting ImageDesk" "ImagedeskE.guide/Starting ImageDesk"
@Next "Configuration"
@Toc "M1_TOUSE"

Starting ImageDesk
==================

   Due to my experiences, the stacksize is not growing much beyond the
2KB border. Therefore the default size of 4096 Bytes will be sufficient
in most cases. If you work mainly with images much wider than 1000
pixels its more secure to increase the stacksize to 8KB.

   ImageDesk could be started from a shell or by Workbench. Currently
there are three arguments and tooltypes, resp., allowed:

   -     @{b}PREFS=<Dateiname>@{ub} - ImageDesk tries to load the prefsfile
     @{b}<Dateiname>@{ub} at programstart. If this file could not be found or it
     is not a valid ImageDesk prefsfile, default values will be used.

   -     @{b}CAT=<Dateiname>@{ub} - ImageDesk opens the catalog file @{b}<Dateiname>@{ub}
     immediately at the programstart.

   -     @{b}VILLAGEMODE@{ub} - (for usage in conjunction with a picasso only)
     If the CyberGraphics software is installed on the system, ImageDesk
     will use it for its specail screens in 8/15/16/24 bitdepth by
     default.  if VILLAGEMODE is set, it is tryed to use the standard
     Picasso drivers instead.

   If no configuration file has been specified at programstart,
ImageDesk will try to find the file @{b}ImageDesk.idprefs@{ub} in the current
directory.  The first time you start ImageDesk, it won't find a
configuration file, of course.  In this case, ImageDesk reports about
it and you will be asked for screenmode and screenfont. The other
values will be set to defaults.  After that procedure a prefsfile will
be saved immediately. Nevertheless it is recommended to set all the
preferences values to your own requirements by selecting the menu items
@{b}System Prefs Window@{ub} and @{b}Viewer Prefs Window@{ub} (see also @{i}Configuration@{ui}).


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration" "ImagedeskE.guide/Configuration"
@Next "Menu"
@Prev "Starting ImageDesk"
@Toc "M1_TOUSE"

Configuration
=============

   The configuration adjustments in ImageDesk have been splitted in two
major groups:

   @{b}*@{ub} System preferences

   @{b}*@{ub} Viewer preferences

   Therefore, two preferences windows are available:

   -     @{b}System Prefs Window@{ub} - To configure ImageDesk's main environment

   -     @{b}Viewer Prefs Window@{ub} - To configure ImageDesk's handling of the
     picture viewers

   These windows could be opened by selecting one of the menu items
@{b}System Prefs Window@{ub} or @{b}Viewer Prefs Window@{ub}.


 @{" System Prefs " Link "System Prefs"} 
 @{" Viewer Prefs " Link "Viewer Prefs"} 


@EndNode

@Node "System Prefs" "ImagedeskE.guide/System Prefs"
@Next "Viewer Prefs"
@Toc "Configuration"

System Prefs
------------

   The data of the valid screenmode is displayed in the frame titled
@{i}Screen@{ui}. A mouse click on the @{b}?@{ub}-button opens a screenmode requester
where a new screenmode can be selected. It is also possible to choose
higher values for width and height than the screen's visible sizes. In
this case it will be opened as an autoscroll screen.

   The frame titled @{i}Font@{ui} can be handled the same way. Here, the font
for screen and windows of ImageDesk is displayed and can be changed.

   @{i}Caution:@{ui} If screenmode or font has been changed and you want to
leave this window by pressing the @{b}USE@{ub} or @{b}Save@{ub} button, all thumbnail
objects will be removed.

   The third framed area of this window groups some gadgets where the
xpkmode to use, an encryption password if supported and the efficiency
of packing has to be specified.  If XPK is not installed these gadgets
are disabled.

   Other preferences gadgets which could not be classified to a
specific group are:

@{b}Output Window@{ub}
     Here the string for specifiying the attributes of the external
     viewer console window has to be edited. It is very important for
     this string to contain @{b}SCREEN=IMAGEDESK@{ub} at the end.  Otherwise,
     this console window won't open on ImageDesk's screen.

@{b}Max. entries per catalog@{ub}
     This is a slider gadget which allows to change the entry limit of
     the catalog files.  If a scaned directory contains of more entries
     than specified here, there will be generated as many catalog files
     as neccessary to store all its thumbnails.  Should more than one
     catalog file be used for a single scan, the files will be numbered
     and its filename will get this number as an filename extension.

@{b}Use XPK for Catalogs@{ub}
     This gadget is displayed disabled if XPK has not been installed.
     Otherwise, it determines if XPK is used for saving catalog files.

@{b}Dither Thumbnail Images@{ub}
     Since ImageDesk has to deal with a limited number of colours, the
     thumbnail images are not always in best quality, especially if the
     images contain of fine colour runs. If this gadget is selected a
     bigger colourspace is simulated by the use of @{i}ordered dithering@{ui}.
     However, using dithering not always results in a better quality of
     the thumbnail images as the pixelspace is to small to cheat the
     eyes perfectly. Another disadvantage is that dithered images could
     not be packed as effectively.

@{b}Save Project Icons@{ub}
     This gadget determines if an icon should be created for each
     generated catalog file. Creating project icons for catalog file
     has a big advantage.  Later, it is possible start ImageDesk and
     load a catalog file with a single mouse click.

   There are four additional buttons, horizontaly spreaded at the
bottom of the window:

@{b}Save@{ub}
     The edited configuration is saved in the current directory and
     gets the filename @{b}ImageDesk.idprefs@{ub}. After this, the window will be
     closed and the changed values will be used in ImageDesk.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     The edited configuration is used immediately and the window will
     be closed.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     In a filerequester you are prompted for a prefsfile which is
     loaded afterwards.  The window remains open to let the user make
     further changes to the loaded prefs.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     The window is closed, all changes will be dismissed.


@EndNode

@Node "Viewer Prefs" "ImagedeskE.guide/Viewer Prefs"
@Prev "System Prefs"
@Toc "Configuration"

Viewer Prefs
------------

   This window is used to select which viewer has to be taken for each
supported image format. To select, click on one radio button of @{b}custom
screen@{ub}, @{b}external@{ub} or @{b}window@{ub}.

   @{i}Remarks:@{ui}

   @{b}*@{ub} If the `Tower JPEG Codec' has not been installed, the corresponding
     buttons are disabled.

   To specify an external viewer, you have to type the viewer name and
the arguments you want to use. Instead of a filename type @{b}%s@{ub}.  A small
example:

   Supposed you want to use the picture viewer called @{i}GigaView@{ui} and
usally you would call this viewer:
                  GigaView <filename> SCREENBEHIND
   In the corresponding gadget you would have to type the following
string:
                  GigaView %s SCREENBEHIND

   @{i}Caution:@{ui} you have to set the whole path instead of the viewer name
only. Otherwise ImageDesk may not find it.

   The preferences in the framed area named @{i}Internal Viewer Prefs@{ui} are
meaningless for external viewers and partly meaningless for the most
image formats.

@{b}Display Screens@{ub}
     With this cycle gadget you tell ImageDesk how to determine the
     custom screens for displaying the images.

        -     @{i}autoscreen@{ui} - ImageDesk tries to find optimal values for
          screen mode and screen size by itself.

        -     @{i}requester@{ui} - Everytime an image has to be displayed, the
          user will be asked for a screen mode by a requester.

        -     @{i}global@{ui} - Fixed screen ids will be used. The user is
          responsible for @{i}Global CLUT Screen@{ui} and @{i}Global DCOL Screen@{ui} to
          have valid values.

@{b}Display Size@{ub}
     Which size the images should be displayed has to be determined
     here.  These values are meaningless for the external viewers.
        -     @{i}original@{ui} - The image will be displayed in original size.

        -     @{i}small@{ui} - The image will be displayed in half the hight and
          half the width.

        -     @{i}tiny@{ui} - The image will be displayed in a quarter the hight
          and a quarter the width.  @{i}Caution:@{ui} The values in @{b}Display Size@{ub}
     are only meaningful for the image formats PCD and JPEG, yet.

@{b}Orientation@{ub}
     These adjustments will cause the following:

        -     @{i}Auto@{ui} - PCD only: Tries to find out the orientation by
          itself.

        -     @{i}Force Landscape@{ui} - PCD only: Displays images in landscape
          mode.

        -     @{i}Force Portrait@{ui} - PCD only: Displays images in portrait
          mode.

        -     @{i}Upside Down@{ui} - all formats: Displays images mirrored to
          the x-axxis.

        -     @{i}Left to Right@{ui} - PCD only: Displays images mirrored to the
          y-axxis.

@{b}Global CLUT Screen@{ub}
     After clicking on the @{b}?@{ub}-button a screenrequester appears where you
     have to choose an 8-bit screen. This selected screenmode is used
     for displaying all images containing upto 256 colors. This setting
     is only significant if @{i}Display Screens@{ui} is set to @{i}global@{ui}.

@{b}Global DCOL Screen@{ub}
     Same as @{i}Global CLUT Screen@{ui}, with the difference that a screenmode
     for all images containing more than 256 colors has to be choosen.

     @{i}Remark:@{ui} it is quite possible to choose an 8-bit screenmode, but
     the display quality will be not very satisfying.

@{b}Dither 8-Bit Displays@{ub}
     If this gadget is checked, the images in 8 bit illustration (this
     is valid for the window viewers and for the 8-bit screen viewers)
     are displayed dithered.  This improves the display quality of the
     image, but slows down the procedure a bit. Only images which
     contain more than 256 colors will be dithered. This means all
     15/16/24/32 bit pictures and HAM images.

@{b}Use Original Palette@{ub}
     If checked, this gadged says that the windows viewer will use the
     original color palette of the pictures. Therefore, it is
     meaningful for images which contains up to 256 colors, only. If
     `Use Original Palette' is activated, ImageDesk temporarily (to be
     more specific, for the duration a picture is displayed) switches
     its palette to the one of the picture.  This will cause a somewhat
     strange looking user interface but it will decrease the the time
     for building up an image @{i}dramatically@{ui} and will avoid quality
     losses. In the other case the image will be converted to 24-bit
     RGB row by row and scaled to 8-bit RGB, afterwards (for the
     insiders: RRRGGGBB).

@{b}Delay@{ub}
     The maximum duration time an image has to be displayed (in 1/10
     seconds).  After all, the display could be closed at any time (any
     keystroke or mouse button when screen viewers are used, ESC-key or
     CloseGadget when the Window viewers are used).

   The four additional buttons @{b}SAVE@{ub}, @{b}USE@{ub}, @{b}LOAD@{ub} and @{b}CANCEL@{ub} have the same
meaning as they have in the System Prefs window.


@EndNode

